She likes you.

264
00:17:40,093 --> 00:17:42,290
She's very friendly.

265
00:17:42,300 --> 00:17:47,462
<i>Well, she was friendly to you,</i>
<i>not to me.</i>

266
00:17:47,472 --> 00:17:49,592
Well, it's 'cause I know her.

267
00:17:49,602 --> 00:17:54,069
Is she married?

268
00:17:54,079 --> 00:17:55,298
I don't think so.

269
00:17:55,308 --> 00:17:56,933
Well, you should ask her out.

270
00:17:56,943 --> 00:17:58,902
Well, I don't know
about that.

271
00:17:58,912 --> 00:18:02,877
Have you been on a date
in the last four years?

272
00:18:02,887 --> 00:18:06,981
Uh...Not really.

273
00:18:06,991 --> 00:18:14,155
So the last time I remember
you going on a date then

274
00:18:14,165 --> 00:18:19,260
would be before...

275
00:18:19,270 --> 00:18:21,265
before the accident.

276
00:18:29,743 --> 00:18:32,845
Started driving again or...

277
00:18:37,117 --> 00:18:39,284
I don't have a car.

278
00:18:44,057 --> 00:18:45,248
<i>[knocking at door]</i>

279
00:18:45,258 --> 00:18:47,258
<i>(boy)</i>
<i>Mom?</i>

280
00:18:51,731 --> 00:18:52,722
Do you have a phone?

281
00:18:52,732 --> 00:18:53,723
What?

282
00:18:53,733 --> 00:18:54,924
I need to call my mom.

283
00:18:54,934 --> 00:18:56,860
No, sorry.

284
00:18:56,870 --> 00:18:58,428
Do you know
if they have one downstairs?

285
00:18:58,438 --> 00:19:00,438
Sorry.

286
00:19:02,509 --> 00:19:03,500
[sighs]

287
00:19:03,510 --> 00:19:06,445
<i>[distant voices over TV]</i>

288
00:19:13,019 --> 00:19:14,010
<i>(man)</i>
<i>Hey, Erik.</i>

289
00:19:14,020 --> 00:19:15,545
<i>(Erik)</i>
<i>Hi, Mr. Curtis.</i>

290
00:19:15,555 --> 00:19:17,380
Is something wrong?

291
00:19:17,390 --> 00:19:19,421
I can't get inside.

292
00:19:19,431 --> 00:19:21,284
<i>Locked yourself out?</i>

293
00:19:21,294 --> 00:19:23,153
You're locked out?

294
00:19:23,163 --> 00:19:25,560
<i>Here, maybe I can do it.</i>

295
00:19:25,570 --> 00:19:30,565
Come here,
show you a little trick.

296
00:19:30,575 --> 00:19:32,796
<i>I do this myself</i>
<i>a couple of times</i>

297
00:19:32,806 --> 00:19:34,631
<i>when I lock myself out.</i>

298
00:19:34,641 --> 00:19:35,632
Yeah.

299
00:19:35,642 --> 00:19:36,633
<i>Take a credit card,</i>

300
00:19:36,643 --> 00:19:39,107
<i>slip it in,</i>

301
00:19:39,117 --> 00:19:42,744
<i>wiggle it around...</i>

302
00:19:42,754 --> 00:19:43,740
<i>there you go.</i>

303
00:19:43,750 --> 00:19:44,841
<i>(Erik)</i>
<i>Thanks, Mr. Curtis.</i>

304
00:19:44,851 --> 00:19:46,543
<i>(Mr. Curtis)</i>
<i>No problem.</i>

305
00:19:46,553 --> 00:19:47,744
<i>Tell your mom and dad</i>
<i>I said hi.</i>

306
00:19:47,754 --> 00:19:48,745
<i>(Erik)</i>
<i>Okay.</i>

307
00:19:48,755 --> 00:19:51,390
Tell your mom and dad
I said hi.

308
00:19:55,261 --> 00:19:58,626
Tell your mom and dad
I said hi.

309
00:19:58,636 --> 00:20:03,159
(man)
So you were licensed
in the State of Delaware, right?

310
00:20:03,169 --> 00:20:04,327
So how can the government

311
00:20:04,337 --> 00:20:06,329
say it was wrong for you
to practice architecture?

312
00:20:06,339 --> 00:20:07,530
I initiated business

313
00:20:07,540 --> 00:20:10,233
before I had
the physical license document.

314
00:20:10,243 --> 00:20:11,534
I passed the test,

315
00:20:11,544 --> 00:20:14,270
but apparently
that doesn't matter.

316
00:20:14,280 --> 00:20:15,472
And you can get fined
for that?

317
00:20:15,482 --> 00:20:16,639
You can go to jail for that.

318
00:20:16,649 --> 00:20:18,375
This is pretty serious,
okay, you know?

319
00:20:18,385 --> 00:20:20,443
I mean, I--
and if I don't go to jail,

320
00:20:20,453 --> 00:20:21,978
I'll probably lose my job,

321
00:20:21,988 --> 00:20:25,315
and I don't think the company's
gonna protect me, so...

322
00:20:25,325 --> 00:20:27,517
Sounds like a kafka novel.

323
00:20:27,527 --> 00:20:29,527
That's crazy.

324
00:20:34,167 --> 00:20:35,158
Hey there, Bill.

325
00:20:35,168 --> 00:20:37,903
<i>How's everything going?</i>

326
00:20:40,674 --> 00:20:46,141
Hey, you work here
all night or...

327
00:20:46,151 --> 00:20:47,137
<i>Yeah.</i>

328
00:20:47,147 --> 00:20:48,805
Yeah, every day, huh?

329
00:20:48,815 --> 00:20:51,479
Yeah, just Sunday
to Friday.

330
00:20:51,489 --> 00:20:53,877
Man, I don't know--
I don't know how you do it.

331
00:20:53,887 --> 00:20:57,147
I mean, I--I don't think
I could do that,

332
00:20:57,157 --> 00:20:59,783
Stay up all night
and everything.

333
00:20:59,793 --> 00:21:00,850
You get used to it.

334
00:21:00,860 --> 00:21:02,385
Yeah?

335
00:21:02,395 --> 00:21:06,156
Yeah, I guess it's just like,
you know, anything else, huh?

336
00:21:06,166 --> 00:21:12,100
Now, what does that do
for, you know, like--

337
00:21:12,110 --> 00:21:13,897
you know, with your wife--
I mean--

338
00:21:13,907 --> 00:21:16,132
you know, it seems
like everybody just--

339
00:21:16,142 --> 00:21:19,078
[vacuum cleaner whirring]

340
00:21:21,047 --> 00:21:24,946
Bill, you all right?

341
00:21:24,956 --> 00:21:25,942
Bill.

342
00:21:25,952 --> 00:21:27,677
[squeals]

343
00:21:27,687 --> 00:21:29,951
I just have to--
are you--

344
00:21:29,961 --> 00:21:31,681
something wr--
did I s--

345
00:21:31,691 --> 00:21:33,350
Um...
Okay.

346
00:21:33,360 --> 00:21:36,558
Could you...

347
00:21:36,568 --> 00:21:38,855
Hey, listen, if I said something
to upset you or something,

348
00:21:38,865 --> 00:21:39,856
I just, you know...

349
00:21:39,866 --> 00:21:41,358
Oh, I'm gonna get this.

350
00:21:41,368 --> 00:21:42,592
Have a good weekend,
all right?

351
00:21:42,602 --> 00:21:46,267
Yes, yes.

352
00:21:46,277 --> 00:21:47,998
(man)
Why are you
always nagging me?

353
00:21:48,008 --> 00:21:49,566
<i>You come home.</i>
<i>You nag, you nag, you nag.</i>

354
00:21:49,576 --> 00:21:50,734
<i>(woman)</i>
<i>I'm not nagging.</i>

355
00:21:50,744 --> 00:21:52,035
<i>(man)</i>
<i>Do you know how hard I work,</i>

356
00:21:52,045 --> 00:21:53,303
<i>and I've got to put up</i>
<i>with this?</i>

357
00:21:53,313 --> 00:21:54,738
<i>(woman)</i>
<i>What kind of father are you?</i>

358
00:21:54,748 --> 00:21:55,805
<i>(man)</i>
<i>Look at you.</i>

359
00:21:55,815 --> 00:21:57,807
(Billy Corgan)
# When I go, #

360
00:21:57,817 --> 00:22:00,815
# a sky of blue,
a pale breeze, #

361
00:22:00,825 --> 00:22:03,618
# as if god knew permanence #

362
00:22:03,628 --> 00:22:05,415
# has graced this thought. #

363
00:22:05,425 --> 00:22:06,416
<i>[arguing continues]</i>

364
00:22:06,426 --> 00:22:08,184
# A silent prayer, #

365
00:22:08,194 --> 00:22:11,226
# an open wound,
a melody. #

366
00:22:11,236 --> 00:22:13,895
# That I renew
with who I am #

367
00:22:13,905 --> 00:22:17,799
# and who I was then. #

368
00:22:17,809 --> 00:22:20,568
# I am true... #

369
00:22:20,578 --> 00:22:22,737
[loud thump]

370
00:22:22,747 --> 00:22:26,341
# as I am born in you. #

371
00:22:26,351 --> 00:22:27,437
[thumping]

372
00:22:27,447 --> 00:22:28,705
<i>(woman)</i>
<i>I hate you!</i>

373
00:22:28,715 --> 00:22:30,540
(Billy Corgan)
# and you are all alone. #

374
00:22:30,550 --> 00:22:31,775
<i>(man)</i>
<i>Sadie, shut up!</i>

375
00:22:31,785 --> 00:22:33,948
[clanging]

376
00:22:33,958 --> 00:22:41,623
(Billy Corgan)
# and you are more than now. #

377
00:22:41,633 --> 00:22:47,228
# In love again
with the girl. #

378
00:22:47,238 --> 00:22:52,133
# A smile, I'll feign. #

379
00:22:52,143 --> 00:22:53,630
Are you okay?

380
00:22:53,640 --> 00:22:55,904
You say something?

381
00:22:55,914 --> 00:22:58,006
Are you okay?

382
00:22:58,016 --> 00:23:00,408
Your eye looks bruised.

383
00:23:00,418 --> 00:23:01,404
No, I'm fine.

384
00:23:01,414 --> 00:23:05,046
I heard you guys
fighting before.

385
00:23:05,056 --> 00:23:07,549
<i>Oh, that's nothing.</i>

386
00:23:07,559 --> 00:23:09,179
I'm sorry
if we're being too loud.

387
00:23:09,189 --> 00:23:11,653
No. No, it's fine.

388
00:23:11,663 --> 00:23:12,916
Yeah, because
you're so quiet,

389
00:23:12,926 --> 00:23:16,019
and I hardly ever see you
coming or going.

390
00:23:16,029 --> 00:23:18,760
I didn't even know
you exist.

391
00:23:18,770 --> 00:23:21,363
Thank you.

392
00:23:21,373 --> 00:23:25,767
Well, it was nice
meeting you.

393
00:23:25,777 --> 00:23:29,004
Thank you.

394
00:23:29,014 --> 00:23:34,009
(Billy Corgan)
# To a man going up suddenly #

395
00:23:34,019 --> 00:23:35,438
# whose life is touched #

396
00:23:35,448 --> 00:23:39,647
# by a ray of happiness. #

397
00:23:39,657 --> 00:23:41,344
# Can you guess? #

398
00:23:41,354 --> 00:23:45,320
# There's no way out
but to climb halfway in. #

399
00:23:45,330 --> 00:23:51,026
# The other half
is left to rot in the sun. #

400
00:23:51,036 --> 00:23:55,797
# I am true, #

401
00:23:55,807 --> 00:24:01,236
# as I am born in you. #

402
00:24:01,246 --> 00:24:06,374
# And you are all alone. #

403
00:24:06,384 --> 00:24:12,113
# And we are more than now. #

404
00:24:12,123 --> 00:24:17,085
# Yes, we are more than now. #

405
00:24:17,095 --> 00:24:23,091
# We are more than now. #

406
00:24:23,101 --> 00:24:27,896
# #

407
00:24:27,906 --> 00:24:30,293
(woman)
The average person
sleeps for 20 years

408
00:24:30,303 --> 00:24:32,162
over the course of a lifetime.

409
00:24:32,172 --> 00:24:35,165
Six of those years
are spent dreaming.

410
00:24:35,175 --> 00:24:36,466
The scientific term

411
00:24:36,476 --> 00:24:38,268
for being aware
that you are dreaming

412
00:24:38,278 --> 00:24:40,070
is lucid dreaming.

413
00:24:40,080 --> 00:24:41,604
Once you become lucid,

414
00:24:41,614 --> 00:24:44,974
it is possible
to actively control your dreams.

415
00:24:44,984 --> 00:24:47,077
Some people
can naturally do this.

416
00:24:47,087 --> 00:24:48,411
For others,
it must be learned.

417
00:24:48,421 --> 00:24:49,813
[sneezes]

418
00:24:49,823 --> 00:24:53,650
Small windows of time exist
during the ritual of sleep

419
00:24:53,660 --> 00:24:57,087
when it is possible
to begin lucid dreaming.

420
00:24:57,097 --> 00:24:59,856
But it can become a door
to another world

421
00:24:59,866 --> 00:25:02,158
where you have
complete control,

422
00:25:02,168 --> 00:25:04,661
a world
where your wildest fantasies

423
00:25:04,671 --> 00:25:06,739
can come true.

424
00:25:22,489 --> 00:25:25,487
[ominous music]

425
00:25:25,497 --> 00:25:33,432
# #

426
00:25:38,238 --> 00:25:40,238
<i>[distant dog barking]</i>

427
00:25:52,519 --> 00:25:54,519
Karen?

428
00:26:12,772 --> 00:26:15,637
<i>Karen?</i>

429
00:26:15,647 --> 00:26:17,772
Hello.
Hey.

430
00:26:17,782 --> 00:26:21,109
I didn't know
you were gonna be here.

431
00:26:21,119 --> 00:26:25,547
Well, somebody
has to get groceries.

432
00:26:25,557 --> 00:26:27,444
No, I know, but I didn't know
where you'd gone.

433
00:26:27,454 --> 00:26:30,389
You didn't leave a note or...

434
00:26:32,926 --> 00:26:34,284
Can I look at what you got,

435
00:26:34,294 --> 00:26:39,127
because we probably shouldn't be
buying the same thing?

436
00:26:39,137 --> 00:26:41,057
Well, why don't you
just eat what you get

437
00:26:41,067 --> 00:26:42,792
and I'll eat what I get?

438
00:26:42,802 --> 00:26:44,761
How about that?

439
00:26:44,771 --> 00:26:49,708
[woman speaking indistinctly
over P.A.]

440
00:26:54,514 --> 00:26:55,839
What, are you
just gonna follow me

441
00:26:55,849 --> 00:26:57,007
around the store
all night?

442
00:26:57,017 --> 00:26:58,241
Yeah, I used to do it
all the time

443
00:26:58,251 --> 00:26:59,709
when we first started dating.

444
00:26:59,719 --> 00:27:00,844
What?

445
00:27:00,854 --> 00:27:02,479
Yeah, I used to--
wherever we'd go,

446
00:27:02,489 --> 00:27:03,680
I'd walk behind you.

447
00:27:03,690 --> 00:27:06,087
You never noticed?

448
00:27:06,097 --> 00:27:08,356
No.

449
00:27:08,366 --> 00:27:09,853
Why would you do that?

450
00:27:09,863 --> 00:27:13,395
Well, I liked how
every single guy

451
00:27:13,405 --> 00:27:16,159
would be, you know,
looking at you,

452
00:27:16,169 --> 00:27:20,935
every one that would go by,
and, you know, you were mine.

453
00:27:20,945 --> 00:27:23,876
Don't do that.

454
00:27:30,083 --> 00:27:32,083
[hums]

455
00:27:39,492 --> 00:27:42,757
<i>Oh, well, well, well.</i>

456
00:27:42,767 --> 00:27:44,054
<i>Oh, yeah.</i>

457
00:27:44,064 --> 00:27:47,529
Embarrassing me.

458
00:27:47,539 --> 00:27:49,597
Are you married?

459
00:27:49,607 --> 00:27:52,538
<i>[distant voices]</i>

460
00:27:54,007 --> 00:27:57,105
<i>I used to count--</i>
<i>I used to count</i>

461
00:27:57,115 --> 00:27:59,441
<i>Each one</i>
<i>that used to go by.</i>

462
00:27:59,451 --> 00:28:01,905
One. There's goes one.
There goes another one.

463
00:28:01,915 --> 00:28:03,340
Don't do that.
What? Do what?

464
00:28:03,350 --> 00:28:05,108
Look around.
Would you look around?

465
00:28:05,118 --> 00:28:07,610
You see anybody looking at me?
Do you?

466
00:28:07,620 --> 00:28:10,113
Do you see anybody
looking at me?

467
00:28:10,123 --> 00:28:11,381
Yeah, I know you used
to do that,

468
00:28:11,391 --> 00:28:12,916
and I know
when you stopped doing it too

469
00:28:12,926 --> 00:28:14,384
and everybody else
stopped doing it.

470
00:28:14,394 --> 00:28:18,526
come on, come on.
That's when you stopped.

471
00:28:18,536 --> 00:28:21,467
[whimpering]

472
00:28:24,904 --> 00:28:26,904
Leave me alone.

473
00:28:30,643 --> 00:28:35,777
[man speaking indistinctly
over P.A.]

474
00:28:35,787 --> 00:28:38,780
[solemn music]

475
00:28:38,790 --> 00:28:46,725
# #

476
00:28:53,800 --> 00:28:56,731
(woman)
In order to lucid dream,

477
00:28:56,741 --> 00:28:59,262
you must first remember
your dreams.

478
00:28:59,272 --> 00:29:01,264
It is necessary
to start a journal,

479
00:29:01,274 --> 00:29:03,900
keeping a daily log
of your dreams.

480
00:29:03,910 --> 00:29:05,902
You will start
to recognize patterns

481
00:29:05,912 --> 00:29:08,438
and reoccurring
characteristics.

482
00:29:08,448 --> 00:29:10,974
When dreaming,
these characteristics

483
00:29:10,984 --> 00:29:13,043
can be used
to help tell yourself

484
00:29:13,053 --> 00:29:15,612
that you are,
in fact, dreaming.

485
00:29:15,622 --> 00:29:17,313
This will facilitate lucidity.

486
00:29:17,323 --> 00:29:20,259
[birds chirping]

487
00:29:32,539 --> 00:29:35,337
[tires squealing]

488
00:29:35,347 --> 00:29:36,333
[gasps]

489
00:29:36,343 --> 00:29:39,207
[whimpers]

490
00:29:39,217 --> 00:29:42,711
Oh.

491
00:29:42,721 --> 00:29:44,007
Yeah, it's--

492
00:29:44,017 --> 00:29:46,643
It's the same material
as my cleaning gloves.

493
00:29:46,653 --> 00:29:49,484
<i>[man grumbling indistinctly]</i>

494
00:29:49,494 --> 00:29:53,154
[sirens wailing]

495
00:29:53,164 --> 00:29:54,851
Can I buy a hotdog here too?

496
00:29:54,861 --> 00:29:57,492
[grumbles indistinctly]

497
00:29:57,502 --> 00:30:00,495
[thunderous rumbling]

498
00:30:00,505 --> 00:30:03,435
[sirens wailing]

499
00:30:11,778 --> 00:30:14,713
[building rumbles]

500
00:30:17,650 --> 00:30:20,582
[loud thudding]

501
00:30:20,592 --> 00:30:24,490
Building's falling down.

502
00:30:26,326 --> 00:30:30,162
Ah.

503
00:30:34,968 --> 00:30:37,966
[gentle music]

504
00:30:37,976 --> 00:30:41,236
# #

505
00:30:41,246 --> 00:30:44,239
[light-hearted music]

506
00:30:44,249 --> 00:30:48,943
# #

507
00:30:48,953 --> 00:30:50,874
I forgot my clothes.

508
00:30:50,884 --> 00:30:53,819
[indistinct chatting]

509
00:30:59,125 --> 00:31:01,260
[zapping on TV]

510
00:31:37,964 --> 00:31:39,356
[man over TV]
That's right, folks.

511
00:31:39,366 --> 00:31:40,690
<i>You will get everything,</i>

512
00:31:40,700 --> 00:31:43,860
<i>I mean absolutely everything,</i>
<i>for $19.99.</i>

513
00:31:43,870 --> 00:31:46,896
<i>If you call right now,</i>
<i>we'll throw in our bonus gift.</i>

514
00:31:46,906 --> 00:31:50,038
<i>We've got copper</i>
<i>condiment shakers.</i>

515
00:31:50,048 --> 00:31:52,769
<i>Holy cow, it's a $50 value.</i>
<i>Can you believe it?</i>

516
00:31:52,779 --> 00:31:54,304
<i>Call now.</i>
<i>1-800--</i>

517
00:31:54,314 --> 00:31:57,249
[humming]

518
00:31:58,818 --> 00:32:00,043
Can I help you?

